===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|solstice}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|solstitium}}, from {{m|la|sol||sun}} + {{m|la|sto||stand}} (as in English {{m|en|solar}} and {{m|en|resist}}), from {{m|la|sistō||I stand still}}, both from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} roots.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈsɒl.stɪs/|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# One of the two points in the [[ecliptic]] at which the sun is furthest from the celestial equator. This corresponds to one of two days in the [[year]] when the [[day]] is either longest or shortest.
#* '''2010''', Capt Sp Meek, [https://books.google.com/books?id=ZNrtnH9kvYYC&pg=PP8&dq=solstice&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CD4Q6AEwBji0AWoVChMI6YaS8uWsxwIVkiqICh32vgDd#v=onepage&q=solstice&f=false The Solar Magnet]
#*: The point at which the sun is nearest to the south pole we call the winter '''solstice''', and the opposite point, the summer '''solstice'''.

